The colorimetric conditions were also optimized (
                           Fig. S7
                        ) and were consistent with those of the RF detection. The smartphone-integrated platform (
                           Fig. S8
                        ) was utilized to photograph color of the sensing system upon addition of different concentrations of GLP. Considering that the color changed from pink purple to green after adding GLP, the RGB ratio (G/R) corresponding to the green channel and the red channel was fitted against the GLP concentration. From Fig. 5

                        A, the G/R acquired by the smartphone-integrated platform gradually changed with the increase of GLP concentration. Further, the G/R value versus GLP concentrations were shown to have an admirable linear correlation in 0.20–6.67 mg/L (R2 = 0.9914) (Fig. 5
                        B). The corresponding regression equation was presented as G/R = 0.0342[C] + 0.8009 ([C]: the concentration of GLP) with a LOD of 141.39 µg/L (3σ/k). Consequently, by virtue of integrating advantages of smartphone and the 3D-printed mini-device, the N-CDs@PCN-222 sensor can realize accurate quantitative analysis of GLP, avoiding the effect of natural light from the environment and poor resolution by naked-eyes. Although the visual detection option displayed a lower sensitivity than the RF mode, which offered a promising sight for preliminarily semi-quantitative screening of GLP in resource-constrained regions. The linear range and LOD of the portable sensing were comparable to previous visual detection methods (
                           Table S3
                        ). More importantly, the GLP colorimetric assay by N-CDs@PCN-222 depended on the intrinsic color variation of the sensor rather than extrinsic catalysts and chromogenic substrates which could impair detection sensitivity. To summarize, the platform was fast-responsive and possessed easy-to-access results for immediate pre-warning of GLP in practical scenarios.
